I think a good rule of thumb is ;

If the artist knew what it needed they would have done it in mixing

They are coming to us mostly for our take, our confidence, our objectivity. In my world there more I try to second guess what the artist “wants” the worse things go

As a producer and a music director, sequencing is an art form that hinges on momentum. 

I’d bet mastering for ‘cohesion’ is almost always a detriment to that! Please attend to the individual songs, but understand the energy transfer from one song to the next and attend to that as well!
@Rollmottle has done that so well for me for the last 3 eps he’s mastered for me!

Will try different things based on the music. No one size fits all here. RX, Serato, Ableton, Logic, PT, even untitled (!) have won depending on the record, how far it needs to go, is varispeed cool (usually sounds better to me) or not!

I’ve yet to find one that I can tell out the gate will be better without listening

@Nomograph Mastering voodoo is crazy though for real

@Nomograph Mastering before using RX, I was using the toolset in wavelab. 

Correct error function. 

Also zoom in and pencil tool.

@cian riordan @Berlin I appreciate the supportive words 🙂 
I got this gig through a referral from someone who doesn’t normally give many referrals so I’ve got some trust equity here.
But these are NOT the first impressions I’m out here trying to make (and wouldn’t be my position in my career if bad first impressions were my De facto modus operandi) that’s what bums me out the most…
